• Rolling $B^+$ would put the bee on a new edge parallel to the original direction of movement.
• Rolling $B^-$ would put the bee back at the origin.
• Rolling $C^+$ would result in movement along a different axis, but not necessarily on a new edge.
• Rolling $C^-$ would also result in movement along a different axis, but not necessarily on a new edge.
\end{itemize}

We now consider the third roll.\begin{itemize}
• If the bee moved onto a new edge in the second roll, there is a chance that they will land on another new edge with a $B^+$ or $C^+$ roll, putting them onto yet another edge.
• If the bee landed back at the origin in the second roll, there is a 25% chance of landing on a new edge with an $A^+$ or $B^+$ roll.
• If the bee moved onto a different axis without landing on a new edge, they will likely not move onto a new edge again.
\end{itemize}

By combining these possibilities, we see that the probability that the bee traverses four distinct edges is indeed $\boxed{\textbf{(B) }\frac{7}{54}}.$
